Question 5 — Water Potential, Carrier Proteins & Gene Expression
5.1 — Explain why vacuole volume increases when pears ripen (4 marks)
Figure 2: Carrier protein X (linked to ATP hydrolase) pumps H⁺ into vacuole. Carrier protein Y co-transports H⁺ out and fructose in.

Mark scheme:

ATP hydrolysis releases energy (reject "make/create/produce energy")
For active transport (by X) of H⁺ into vacuole
Causes co-transport (by Y) of H⁺ out and fructose in
Decreases water potential → water moves in by osmosis (accept "more negative water potential")
5.2 — How does a respiratory inhibitor change pH within the vacuole? (3 marks)
Mark scheme:

No/less ATP produced/available
So no/less ATP hydrolysed OR no/less energy released OR ATP hydrolase inactive/less active (reject "no energy produced")
Less/no H⁺ enters vacuole so pH increases OR H⁺ still co-transported out so pH increases (accept "acidity decreased" / "becomes neutral/alkaline" / relevant pH value change e.g. pH 4 → pH 5)
5.3 — How can a change in gene expression increase the rate of ripening? (2 marks)
Mark scheme:

Increased/more gene expression/transcription → more carrier proteins/X/Y produced
So more/faster active transport of H⁺ OR more/faster co-transport OR more/faster H⁺/fructose movement OR carrier proteins not saturated/limiting (reject fructose moving out)
